        <processinfo id="ref12">
            <head>Processing Information note</head>
            <p>The Mitchell Loeb Papers (TAM 627) was previously named the Mitchell Loeb Drawings (TAM 065) and then the Mitchell Loeb Photographs (PHOTOS 169). Materials were arranged and described by the archivist.</p>
        </processinfo>
        <scopecontent id="ref1">
            <head>Scope and Contents note</head>
            <p>The Mitchell Loeb Papers consist of 223 items total, covering a number of different meda. It includes 35 posters, 141 drawings, seven graphic items, nine pamphlets, 23 black and white photographs, three 8x10 negatives and five newspaper clippings. Dated items range from the mid 1930s to the mid 1950s and consist mainly of work done by Loeb himself for the International Ladies Garment Workers Union (ILGWU) and the 
                <title render="italic">Jewish Daily Forward</title> newspaper.</p>
        </scopecontent>
        <relatedmaterial id="ref4">
            <head>Related Archival Materials</head>
            <p>The Tamiment/Wagner Poster Collection (GRAPHICS 002) includes several posters produced by Mitchell Loeb; works produced by Loeb can be found in the Eugene V. Debs Papers (TAM 020) as well. Other items produced by Mitchell Loeb are also held by the Kheel Center for Labor-Management Documentation and Archives at Cornell University in its International Ladies Garment Workers (ILGWU) Paintings, Photographs, and Memorabilia collection.</p>
        </relatedmaterial>
        <bioghist id="ref11">
            <head>Historical/Biographical Note</head>
            <p>Mitchell Loeb (1889-1968) was an artist and cartoonist whose work reflected his support for labor, liberal Democrats, and Isael. Loeb was born in Poland and came to the United States as a teenager. For a short period after World War I, Loeb was an artist for 
                <emph render="italic">The Jewish Daily Forward</emph> and 
                <emph render="italic">The Jewish Day</emph>. After, he ran a commercial art studio in New York City.</p>
        </bioghist>
